The website's creator, David Bolton,

00:11:41.602 --> 00:11:44.310
gained much of the
information by interviewing

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:47.570
scientists and anthropologists
for many years,

00:11:47.570 --> 00:11:50.420
and I've synthesized a
lot of that for this talk.

00:11:50.420 --> 00:11:53.180
I highly recommend that
you explore this website

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:54.660
for additional information on this

00:11:54.660 --> 00:11:56.800
topic of reading and writing,

00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:59.800
the history of reading and
writing, and especially dyslexia.

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:02.967
I quote from David Bolton,

00:12:02.967 --> 00:12:05.417
"There weren't any cognitive scientists

00:12:05.417 --> 00:12:07.577
"or neuroscientists or psychologists

00:12:07.577 --> 00:12:10.067
"or even child development
experts involved

00:12:10.067 --> 00:12:12.423
"in creating the English writing system.

00:12:13.487 --> 00:12:16.407
"There wasn't any concern for hundreds

00:12:16.407 --> 00:12:18.327
"of millions of children
who would struggle

00:12:18.327 --> 00:12:21.807
"since this code was
created in the 15th Century.

00:12:21.807 --> 00:12:24.367
"There were just a small
number of chancery scribes

00:12:24.367 --> 00:12:26.117
"doing their very best to shove

00:12:26.117 --> 00:12:28.477
"a technology created for Latin

00:12:28.477 --> 00:12:32.670
"into a language it was
never designed for."

00:12:32.670 --> 00:12:36.077
Those who eventually do manage
to overcome the confusion

00:12:36.077 --> 00:12:38.113
and learn how to break the code

00:12:38.113 --> 00:12:40.319
to become phonologically aware

00:12:40.319 --> 00:12:43.060
are able to use the areas of the brain

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:46.720
that reading has recycled
from speech and language,

00:12:46.720 --> 00:12:47.833
these areas here.

00:12:49.870 --> 00:12:53.773
Those who cannot break
this code become dyslexic.

00:12:56.530 --> 00:12:59.180
According to the United
States Department of Education

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:02.935
in 2017, more than 60 percent of U.S.

00:13:02.935 --> 00:13:06.850
K-12 schoolchildren are
reading below proficiency,

00:13:06.850 --> 00:13:09.910
and more than 70 percent writing below

00:13:09.910 --> 00:13:13.800
the level of proficiency
for that grade level.

00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:15.993
Let these stunning numbers sink in.

00:13:18.690 --> 00:13:22.440
Reading is a skill that matters
most to success in school,

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:24.970
and children who fall behind in reading

00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:27.610
are in great academic danger.

00:13:27.610 --> 00:13:30.180
But it's not just the
lack of reading skills

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:32.660
that most endanger these children.

00:13:32.660 --> 00:13:34.960
It's the collateral damage.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:39.170
It's their mind shame
that fates their future,

00:13:39.170 --> 00:13:41.110
as seen on this video clip being shown

00:13:41.110 --> 00:13:43.360
with permission of Children of the Code.

00:13:43.360 --> 00:13:45.397
- My teacher asked me to come

00:13:45.397 --> 00:13:47.710
to the front of the class and read a book,

00:13:47.710 --> 00:13:50.300
and everybody was just staring at me

00:13:50.300 --> 00:13:52.320
and I got real nervous

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:54.390
'cause I didn't wanna mess up or anything.

00:13:54.390 --> 00:13:55.690
And then when I started reading,

00:13:55.690 --> 00:13:58.780
I started messing up, and
I should couldn't help it

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:01.540
and everybody started
laughing at me and stuff.

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:02.980
- The teacher would ask
me to read something,

00:14:02.980 --> 00:14:05.610
and I would read it and
I would get a wrong word

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:07.860
or I would go too slow and
they would make fun of me.

00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:09.380
- I kept messing up on the words

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:11.053
and people kept laughing at me.

00:14:12.550 --> 00:14:15.150
- They said that you
don't know how to read,

00:14:15.150 --> 00:14:19.833
bet you won't be able to know
how to read when you grow up.

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:26.403
- They always laugh at me if
I get too stuck with words.

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:29.256
It makes my heart drop,

00:14:29.256 --> 00:14:32.493
'cause it seems like they
not my friend no more.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:36.770
- The collateral damage
caused by literacy problems

00:14:36.770 --> 00:14:40.270
in the United States alone is immense.

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:43.400
75 percent to 80 percent of students

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:45.540
identified as learning disabled

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:49.520
have their basic deficits
in language and reading.

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:54.460
Academic success, as defined
by high school graduation,

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:57.490
can be predicted by knowing
someone's reading skill

00:14:57.490 --> 00:14:59.563
at the end of third grade.

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:03.090
56 percent of students
with learning disabilities

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:05.763
will drop out of school and be arrested.

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:09.850
60 percent of adolescents in treatment

00:15:09.850 --> 00:15:12.993
for substance abuse have
learning disabilities.

00:15:14.640 --> 00:15:17.760
50 percent of females
with learning disabilities

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:20.570
will be mothers, many
of them single mothers,

00:15:20.570 --> 00:15:24.053
within three to five years
of leaving high school.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:28.282
Learning disabilities and substance abuse

00:15:28.282 --> 00:15:30.375
are the number one reason

00:15:30.375 --> 00:15:33.870
for keeping welfare recipients

00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:36.863
from becoming and remaining employed.

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:41.960
Now I'm gonna turn to discussing

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:44.480
how modern technologies are impacting

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:46.353
reading and writing today.

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:54.180
Least we forget, the human brain

00:15:54.180 --> 00:15:57.560
is an exquisitely adaptable machine.

00:15:57.560 --> 00:15:59.480
Even though written language did not

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:01.130
evolve like spoken language did

00:16:01.130 --> 00:16:03.380
over tens of millions of years ago,

00:16:03.380 --> 00:16:06.180
since the invention of
writing and reading,

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:09.210
the remarkable neuroplasticity
of the human brain

00:16:09.210 --> 00:16:11.560
has supported the rapid formation

00:16:11.560 --> 00:16:16.270
of a highly elaborate
literacy brain circuit.

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:20.728
Literacy is a unique
epigenetic achievement

00:16:20.728 --> 00:16:22.876
that changes what we perceive,

00:16:22.876 --> 00:16:26.340
how we think, and how we feel.

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:28.980
That is, who we are.

00:16:28.980 --> 00:16:31.390
I think it's fair to say
that reading and writing,

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:34.100
perhaps more than any other technology,

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:35.770
have had the greatest impact

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:39.223
on the advancement of Homo
sapiens brain and mind.

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:43.000
As we gain proficiency
in reading and writing,

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.026
the continual use of our
literacy brain circuit

00:16:46.026 --> 00:16:51.026
feeds back, elaborates,
and strengthens itself.

00:16:51.220 --> 00:16:52.680
But just as this brain circuit

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:56.393
developed very rapidly
in evolutionary terms,

00:16:56.393 --> 00:17:01.393
or perhaps because it was so rapid,

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:05.468
this circuit is also
more vulnerable to change

00:17:05.468 --> 00:17:10.468
if not continuously reinforced
by experience and use.

00:17:12.870 --> 00:17:16.010
Only if we continuously
work to develop and use

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:19.340
the elaborated analytical, inferential,

00:17:19.340 --> 00:17:21.610
and empathetic skills that have been

00:17:21.610 --> 00:17:24.910
developed by literacy
will the neural networks

00:17:24.910 --> 00:17:26.550
underlying these skills continue

00:17:26.550 --> 00:17:30.750
to sustain our capacity to be attentive,

00:17:30.750 --> 00:17:33.210
thoughtful, critical thinkers,

00:17:33.210 --> 00:17:38.210
rather than passive consumers
of facts, real or fake.

00:17:42.300 --> 00:17:43.920
Despite alphabetic writing not

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:45.747
changing much since the invention

00:17:45.747 --> 00:17:49.933
of the printing press in the 15th Century,

00:17:52.290 --> 00:17:55.830
modern technologies, particularly
social media technologies,

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:58.300
are having a very rapid
and profound effect

00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:01.700
on writing practices in the 21st Century.

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:04.040
Interestingly, many of
these new technologies

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:06.970
are making less use of
alphabetic writing systems

00:18:06.970 --> 00:18:10.280
and more use, once again, of pictographs,

00:18:10.280 --> 00:18:14.270
as can be seen here, comparing
the Egyptian hieroglyphics

00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:18.090
of 3100 BC to a thank you
note I recently received

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:19.620
from my niece that says

00:18:20.597 --> 00:18:25.597
"Dinner was awesome,
it was a gift, thanks."

00:18:31.227 --> 00:18:33.780
And another example, a Chinese pictograph

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:38.011
for medical marijuana,
originally from 10,000 years ago,

00:18:38.011 --> 00:18:42.643
and a clip art symbol for
medical marijuana from 2017.

00:18:44.830 --> 00:18:48.190
Since the 15th Century,
despite many changes

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:52.730
in spoken English, from Old
English to Middle English

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:56.010
to Early Modern and Late Modern English,

00:18:56.010 --> 00:18:57.930
like here it says then she went

00:18:57.930 --> 00:19:01.813
to speak the whatever English tongue,

00:19:03.259 --> 00:19:07.540
written English has
used the same 26 letters

00:19:07.540 --> 00:19:11.633
to represent the 44 sounds
of English, until now.

00:19:12.510 --> 00:19:14.847
The bottom line reads

00:19:14.847 --> 00:19:19.847
"Then she went to speak this
digital age English tongue."

00:19:23.950 --> 00:19:27.010
Neuroscientists like me,
who specialize in reading,

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:28.960
are frequently asked these days,

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:31.770
how might these rapid
technological changes

00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:34.253
in reading and writing
affect the human mind?

00:19:35.230 --> 00:19:37.690
My colleague Dr. Maryanne Wolf focuses

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:42.010
on exactly this question in
her new book Reader, Come Home.

00:19:42.010 --> 00:19:44.340
I'd like to close with
some of the profound

00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:46.453
insights from this timely book.

00:19:47.780 --> 00:19:51.650
As we move from a literary
and word-based culture

00:19:51.650 --> 00:19:56.650
into a far faster paced
digital and screen-based one,

00:19:56.650 --> 00:20:00.083
we face an existential dilemma
in this new millennium.

00:20:01.971 --> 00:20:04.440
There are many things that would be lost

00:20:04.440 --> 00:20:07.460
if we slowly lose the cognitive patience

00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:10.360
to immerse ourselves in the worlds

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:12.810
that are created by books, and the lives,

00:20:12.810 --> 00:20:14.600
feelings, thoughts, and insights

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:17.010
of the characters who inhabit them.

00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:19.260
In a culture that increasingly rewards

00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:22.200
immediacy, ease, and efficiency,

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:24.640
the demanding time and effort involved

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:27.750
in what Dr. Wolf refers to as deep reading

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:31.310
make it an increasingly embattled entity.

00:20:31.310 --> 00:20:35.640
In closing I ask each of you
to consider this question.

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:38.440
Will the very plasticity
of the literate brain

00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:40.710
as it begins to reflect
the characteristics

00:20:40.710 --> 00:20:43.300
of digital media that we and our children

00:20:43.300 --> 00:20:45.563
are increasingly immersing ourselves in

00:20:45.563 --> 00:20:48.040
precipitate the atrophy of our

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:51.256
most essential thought processes,

00:20:51.256 --> 00:20:55.650
sustained attention, critical analysis,

00:20:55.650 --> 00:20:59.810
empathy, and reflection, and indeed wisdom

00:20:59.810 --> 00:21:02.700
to the detriment of democratic societies

00:21:02.700 --> 00:21:04.730
that critically depend on these,

00:21:04.730 --> 00:21:06.780
the most essential characteristics

00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:09.790
of the enlightened literate individual?

00:21:09.790 --> 00:21:10.623
Thank you.

